Virtual machines first

With virtualization, a hypervisor (like VMware or Microsoft’s Hyper-V) lets one physical server run multiple virtual machines (VMs).

Each VM includes:

its own guest operating system
libraries
application code

That was a huge improvement over “one server = one app,” because it improved isolation and hardware utilization.

The limitation of VMs

VMs are still relatively heavy because every VM carries a full OS.

That means:

slower startup (often tens of seconds to minutes)
more RAM and disk usage
more overhead when scaling lots of small services
Why containers appeared

Containers (for example with Docker) package the application plus its dependencies, but share the host OS kernel instead of each carrying a separate OS.

So containers are:

much lighter
start very fast (often seconds or less)
easier to scale up/down
ideal for microservices and CI/CD pipelines
